// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// FITFORGE v3 — DATA
// 6-day PPL | Thoracic Reset every day | No RDL | No cardio on legs
// Every exercise has condition-specific detail for L4-L5,
// cervical spine, thoracic pain, and forward head posture
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

const PLAN_START = new Date(2026, 2, 10);

// ─── THORACIC RESET (mandatory before every warm-up) ───
const THORACIC_RESET = [
  { name:"Thoracic Foam Roller Extension", detail:"90s (3 positions)", muscles:"Thoracic spine mobility", howTo:"Sit on the floor. Place a foam roller HORIZONTALLY across your upper back, just below your shoulder blades. Interlace your fingers behind your head to support your neck — this is critical, do NOT let your neck hang back unsupported.\n\nKeep your butt on the floor. Engage your core with a slight pelvic tuck. Now slowly lean back, extending your upper back OVER the roller. Allow your chest to open toward the ceiling. You should feel a gentle stretch and maybe some gentle pops — that is normal, those are your stiff thoracic joints mobilizing.\n\nHold each position for 3-4 deep breaths. On each EXHALE, relax a little more over the roller.\n\nThen lift your hips slightly, roll the foam roller UP about 2 inches to the next segment of your thoracic spine, lower your hips back down, and repeat the extension. Cover 3 positions total — from below shoulder blades to mid-back.\n\nIMPORTANT: Only roll your UPPER back (thoracic spine). Do NOT roll your neck or lower back. Keep your abs engaged so your lumbar spine does not arch — all the extension should come from your upper back only.\n\nThis exercise directly addresses the stiffness between your shoulder blades that is causing your thoracic pain. Think of it as feeding your stiff joints with movement and blood flow.", safety:"Support your neck with hands. Do NOT roll lower back or neck. Core stays engaged." },
  { name:"Thoracic Rotation (Side-lying)", detail:"8 each side", muscles:"Thoracic rotation mobility", howTo:"Lie on your RIGHT side. Stack your knees at 90 degrees. Extend both arms straight out in front of you at chest level, palms together.\n\nSlowly sweep your LEFT (top) arm up and over your body to the other side, opening your chest toward the ceiling. Follow your hand with your eyes. Try to get your left shoulder blade toward the floor behind you.\n\nThe KEY: your knees stay stacked and glued together the entire time. The rotation comes ONLY from your thoracic spine, not your lower back or hips. If your knees start to separate, you are rotating from the wrong place.\n\nHold the open position for 2 seconds. Feel the stretch across your chest and the rotation through your upper back. Return slowly.\n\n8 reps each side. This restores the rotation that gets lost from sitting hunched. When your thoracic spine cannot rotate, your neck and lower back are forced to over-rotate to compensate — which is why your neck and lower back also hurt.", safety:"Knees stay stacked. Rotation from upper back only." },
  { name:"Chin Tucks", detail:"15 reps, hold 5s each", muscles:"Deep neck flexors", howTo:"Sit or stand tall. Look straight ahead. Now pull your chin STRAIGHT BACK — as if someone is pushing your chin toward the back of your head. You are creating a 'double chin.' This is the correct movement.\n\nDo NOT tilt your head down or up. The movement is purely horizontal — chin goes backward while your eyes stay looking straight ahead.\n\nHold for 5 seconds. You should feel a gentle stretch at the base of your skull and a light engagement of the muscles at the front of your neck (deep neck flexors). These deep flexors are the muscles that are WEAK and causing your forward head posture and neck pain.\n\n15 reps. Do these EVERY day — even on rest days. At your desk, in your car, standing in line. The more you do chin tucks throughout the day, the faster your neck pain improves.\n\nA useful trick: push two fingers against your chin to give yourself resistance. This makes the deep neck flexors work harder.", safety:"Horizontal movement only. Do NOT tilt head up or down." },
  { name:"Prone Thoracic Extension (Cobra Lite)", detail:"10 reps, hold 3s", muscles:"Thoracic extensors", howTo:"Lie FACE DOWN on the floor. Place your hands beside your shoulders, palms down (like the start of a push-up). Forehead resting on the floor.\n\nGentle engagement: squeeze your shoulder blades together and down (back pocket cue). Now GENTLY lift your chest off the floor 2-3 inches — only 2-3 inches, this is NOT a full cobra or back extension. Your hands provide light support but are not pushing — the lift comes from the muscles BETWEEN your shoulder blades.\n\nHold for 3 seconds at the top. You should feel the muscles between your shoulder blades working. Lower slowly.\n\n10 reps. This is a STRENGTHENING exercise for the thoracic extensors — the muscles that hold your upper back upright. These muscles are weak from being constantly stretched in a rounded posture. By lifting against gravity, you are directly training them.\n\nKEY: keep your lower back relaxed. The lift is ONLY from the upper back. If you feel your lower back tightening, you are lifting too high — reduce the range.", safety:"Only lift 2-3 inches. Lower back stays relaxed. Lift from upper back muscles only." },
  { name:"Scapular Squeezes", detail:"15 reps, hold 5s", muscles:"Rhomboids, mid/lower traps", howTo:"Sit or stand tall. Arms relaxed at your sides.\n\nSqueeze your shoulder blades TOGETHER and DOWN — imagine you are trying to crack a walnut between your shoulder blades while also pushing them toward your back pockets. This is the 'back and down' position.\n\nHold for 5 full seconds. You should feel strong contraction between your shoulder blades. This is EXACTLY where your pain is — and these muscles being weak is WHY you have the pain.\n\n15 reps. The burn you feel is the muscles waking up. Over 4-6 weeks of daily scapular squeezes + the pulling exercises in your program, the pain between your shoulder blades will significantly reduce because these muscles will finally be strong enough to hold your posture.", safety:"Don't shrug shoulders up. Push them DOWN and BACK." },
];

// ─── WARM-UP ───
const WARMUP = [
  { name:"Cat-Cow", detail:"8 reps | 3-1-3-1", muscles:"Entire spine, disc hydration", howTo:"All fours — hands directly under shoulders, knees directly under hips. Your spine starts in a neutral position.\n\nINHALE: Let your belly drop toward the floor, gently lift your chest and tailbone upward (Cow position). Hold 1 second. You should feel a gentle opening through your entire front body.\n\nEXHALE: Round your back toward the ceiling, tuck your chin toward your chest and your tailbone under (Cat position). Hold 1 second.\n\nMove through your PAIN-FREE range only — if full cow (arch) hurts your lower back, reduce the range. If full cat (round) hurts your upper back, reduce the range. Find the comfortable middle.\n\nThis exercise hydrates your L4-L5 disc by alternating compression and decompression, pumping nutrients into the disc tissue. Think of it as a sponge being squeezed and released. It also mobilizes your thoracic spine gently.\n\n8 complete cycles at a slow, controlled pace.", safety:"Pain-free range only. Don't force the extremes." },
  { name:"Bird Dog", detail:"8 each side | 2-2-2-0", muscles:"Core, multifidus, glutes", howTo:"Start on all fours. Brace your core — imagine someone is about to poke your belly, tighten those muscles.\n\nSlowly extend your RIGHT arm forward and LEFT leg backward simultaneously (2 seconds). Your arm, spine, and leg should form one straight line. HOLD 2 seconds.\n\nThe CRITICAL CUE: your hips should NOT rotate or shift. Imagine balancing a glass of water on your lower back. If it would spill, your hips rotated — reduce the speed and range.\n\nReturn slowly (2 seconds). Switch sides.\n\nThis exercise is literally used in DISC REHABILITATION by physiotherapists. It trains the multifidus muscles — small deep muscles that directly stabilize each individual vertebra of your spine, including L4-L5 and your thoracic spine. It also trains anti-rotation, which protects your disc during twisting movements in daily life.", safety:"Hips stay square. Slow and controlled." },
  { name:"Dead Bug", detail:"8 each side | 3-1-2-0", muscles:"Transverse abdominis, deep core", howTo:"Lie on your back. Arms straight up toward the ceiling. Knees bent at 90 degrees, shins parallel to floor.\n\nCRITICAL FIRST STEP: Press your lower back FIRMLY into the floor. There should be ZERO gap between your lower back and the ground. To find this position, imagine pulling your belly button toward the floor while slightly tucking your pelvis.\n\nNow slowly lower your RIGHT arm overhead and LEFT leg toward the floor (3 seconds). Stop JUST BEFORE they touch the floor. Hold 1 second. Return to start (2 seconds).\n\nYour lower back must stay pressed into the floor THE ENTIRE TIME. This is non-negotiable. If your back arches up even slightly, you have gone too far — reduce the range of motion until you can keep it flat.\n\nThis is your #1 core exercise for L4-L5 disc protection. It trains the transverse abdominis (your deep corset muscle) to stabilize your spine during limb movement — exactly what happens during daily activities like reaching for something on a shelf or picking up a bag.", safety:"Lower back MUST stay on floor. Reduce range if it arches." },
  { name:"Hip Flexor Rockback", detail:"8 each side", muscles:"Psoas, rectus femoris (hip flexors)", howTo:"Get into a half-kneeling position — right foot forward, left knee on the ground (use a folded towel under your knee for comfort).\n\nKeep your torso TALL — do not lean forward. Gently shift your hips forward until you feel a stretch in the FRONT of your left hip/thigh.\n\nKEY CUE: Squeeze your LEFT GLUTE while shifting forward. This posteriorly tilts your pelvis, which does two things: (1) it intensifies the hip flexor stretch, and (2) it directly practices the pelvic position that corrects your anterior pelvic tilt.\n\nHold 2 seconds. Return. 8 reps each side.\n\nYour hip flexors are TIGHT from sitting. They are literally pulling the front of your pelvis downward, which increases the curve in your lower back, which increases pressure on your L4-L5 disc. This stretch + glute squeeze directly combats that.", safety:"Squeeze the glute on the kneeling side. Stay tall." },
  { name:"Glute Bridge", detail:"12 reps | 2-2-2-0", muscles:"Glutes, hamstrings", howTo:"Lie on your back, feet flat on floor about hip-width apart, knees bent. Arms by your sides.\n\nDrive through your HEELS (not your toes — your toes can even lift slightly) and squeeze your glutes to lift your hips toward the ceiling (2 seconds up). At the top, your body forms a straight line from shoulders to knees.\n\nSQUEEZE your glutes as HARD as you can and hold for 2 full seconds. This is the most important part — really contract them maximally.\n\nLower slowly (2 seconds). Do NOT let your hips drop quickly.\n\nDo NOT hyperextend past the straight line position — stop when your body is straight, not arched.\n\nYour glutes are likely 'sleeping' from prolonged sitting. When glutes are weak, your lower back picks up the slack, which overloads L4-L5. This bridge wakes them up before training so they actually fire during your workout.", safety:"Straight line at top. Don't hyperextend. Squeeze glutes hard." },
  { name:"Wall Slides", detail:"10 reps | 3-1-3-0", muscles:"Lower traps, serratus anterior", howTo:"Stand with your back flat against a wall. Feet about 6 inches from the wall. Press your head, upper back, and butt against the wall.\n\nPlace your arms in a 'W' position — elbows at 90 degrees, backs of your wrists and hands touching the wall.\n\nSlowly slide your arms UP the wall into a 'Y' position (3 seconds up). The GOAL is to keep your wrists, elbows, and backs of hands in contact with the wall the ENTIRE time.\n\nThis WILL be very hard if your chest and shoulders are tight — and yours are, based on the rounded shoulder posture in your photos. Go as far as you can while maintaining wall contact. Even if you can only slide up 6 inches at first, that is fine. Over weeks, the range will increase.\n\nHold 1 second at your highest point. Slide back down (3 seconds).\n\nThis directly activates the lower trapezius and serratus anterior — the muscles that hold your shoulder blades flat against your ribcage and DOWN away from your ears. These are weak in you, which is why your shoulders round and your upper back hurts between the shoulder blades.", safety:"Back flat on wall. Don't arch lower back. Go only as far as you can with contact." },
  { name:"Band Pull-Apart", detail:"15 reps | 2-1-2-0", muscles:"Rear delts, rhomboids", howTo:"Hold a LIGHT resistance band at shoulder width, arms straight in front at shoulder height.\n\nPull the band apart by squeezing your shoulder blades TOGETHER until the band touches your chest (2 seconds). Hold and SQUEEZE for 1 second — really try to crack that imaginary walnut between your shoulder blades.\n\nReturn slowly (2 seconds). 15 reps.\n\nUse a light band — this is activation work, not strength. This fires the exact muscles that are weak and causing your rounded shoulder posture and thoracic pain. You will feel it precisely in the area where your upper back hurts — that is the right area working.", safety:"Light band. Squeeze shoulder blades at the end." },
  { name:"Leg Swings", detail:"10 each leg", muscles:"Hip mobility", howTo:"Stand next to a wall for balance. Swing your outside leg forward and backward in a controlled pendulum motion. Start small and increase range over 10 reps. Movement comes from the HIP — do not swing your torso.", safety:"Controlled from hip." },
  { name:"Arm Circles", detail:"10 each direction", muscles:"Rotator cuff, shoulders", howTo:"Arms out to sides. Small circles forward, gradually building to large circles over 10 reps. Reverse for 10 more. Warms the rotator cuff for pressing and pulling.", safety:"Start small, build large." },
];

// ─── COOLDOWN ───
const COOLDOWN = [
  { name:"Chest Doorway Stretch", detail:"45s each side", howTo:"Stand in a doorway. Place your forearm on the door frame with elbow at shoulder height, bent 90 degrees. Step your foot forward through the doorway and lean forward until you feel a DEEP stretch across your chest and front of your shoulder.\n\nHold 45 seconds — LONGER than the original plan because your chest is particularly tight and directly contributing to your rounded shoulders and thoracic pain. Breathe into the stretch.\n\nDo this EVERY DAY — even on rest days. Morning and evening if possible. This single stretch done consistently will make more difference to your upper back pain than almost anything else because tight pecs are pulling your shoulders forward, which stretches and weakens the muscles between your shoulder blades." },
  { name:"Cross-Body Shoulder Stretch", detail:"30s each side", howTo:"Bring your right arm across your body at shoulder height. Use your left hand to gently pull it closer. Stretch the back of your shoulder. 30 seconds each side." },
  { name:"Hip Flexor Kneeling Stretch", detail:"45s each side", howTo:"Half-kneeling. Shift hips forward, squeeze back glute. Raise same arm overhead, lean slightly away. Hold 45 seconds. Critical for your anterior pelvic tilt correction — tight hip flexors are pulling your pelvis forward and increasing L4-L5 disc pressure." },
  { name:"Piriformis Figure-4", detail:"30s each side", howTo:"On back. Cross right ankle over left knee. Pull left thigh toward chest. Deep glute/hip stretch. 30 seconds each side." },
  { name:"Hamstring Stretch (Lying)", detail:"30s each side", howTo:"On back. Towel around foot, straighten leg, pull gently. Other leg flat. 30 seconds. This is the spine-neutral way to stretch hamstrings — standing toe touches flex your spine and load L4-L5." },
  { name:"Child's Pose", detail:"60s", howTo:"Kneel, sit hips back onto heels, arms forward, forehead on floor. Breathe deeply into your UPPER BACK — feel it expand between your shoulder blades with each inhale. 60 seconds. This gently decompresses your thoracic spine." },
  { name:"Neck Stretch", detail:"20s each side", howTo:"Tilt ear toward shoulder. Very gentle hand overpressure — DO NOT PULL HARD. Given your cervical issues, keep this extremely gentle. 20 seconds each side." },
  { name:"Thoracic Foam Roller (Final)", detail:"60s", howTo:"Same as Thoracic Reset, but post-workout your muscles are warm so you may get slightly more range. 60 seconds across 2-3 positions. Breathe and relax over the roller." },
  { name:"Supine Twist", detail:"30s each side", howTo:"On back, arms in T. Knees to chest, lower to one side, look opposite direction. Both shoulders stay on floor. 30 seconds each side. Go only as far as comfortable." },
];

